<section xml:id="sec-1-3parametric-questions">
  <title>10.3 Calculus and Parametric Equations</title>

  <exercises xml:id="calculus_parametric">

  <introduction>
    <p>
        We are still interested in lines tangent to points on a curve. They describe how the 
        <m>y</m>-values are changing with respect to the <m>x</m>-values, 
        they are useful in making approximations, and they indicate instantaneous direction of travel.
    </p>
  </introduction>


  <exercise xml:id="sec10-3-concept-mc-02" label="sec10-3-concept-mc-02">
      <title>Exercise: Interpreting a horizontal tangent.</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose a particle moves along a parametric curve and at <m>t=t_0</m> we have
        <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}=0</m> and <m>\dfrac{dx}{dt}\neq 0</m>.
        What does this tell us?
      </p>
    </statement>

    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p>The tangent line to the curve is horizontal at the corresponding point.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Correct. When <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}=0</m> and <m>\dfrac{dx}{dt}\neq 0</m>, 
          the slope of the tangent line to the curve <m>y(x)</m> is <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}=0</m>.</p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="no">
        <statement><p>The particle has stopped moving completely.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p><m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}=0</m> only means the vertical component of motion is zero at that instant.</p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="no">
        <statement><p>The tangent line is vertical at the corresponding point.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>A vertical tangent is associated with <m>\dfrac{dx}{dt}=0</m> and <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}\neq 0</m>.</p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="no">
        <statement><p>The curve must have a local maximum in <m>y</m>.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>A horizontal tangent does not automatically imply a local maximum.</p></feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="sec10-3-concept-mc-03" label="sec10-3-concept-mc-03">
      <title>Exercise: Interpreting concavity for a parametric curve.</title>
    <statement>

      <p>
        At a point on a parametric curve, suppose <m>\dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2}&gt;0</m>.
        Which statement best describes the graph near that point?
      </p>
    </statement>

    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p>The curve is concave up near that point (where the derivative is defined).</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Correct. A positive second derivative indicates concave up behavior.</p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="no">
        <statement><p>The curve must cross the <m>x</m>-axis at that point.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Concavity does not determine whether the curve crosses an axis.</p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="no">
        <statement><p>The tangent line must be horizontal at that point.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Concavity and slope are different ideas.</p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="no">
        <statement><p>The particle must be speeding up at that point.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Concavity of the graph is not the same as speed increasing.</p></feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

