    <exercise xml:id="sec10-3-concept-sata-04" label="sec10-3-concept-sata-04">
    <title>Exercise: Same curve, different parameterizations.</title>
     <statement>
    <p>
      Two particles move according to the parametric equations
      <m>x=t,\ y=t^2</m> and <m>\overline{x}=2t,\ \overline{y}=4t^2</m>.
      Select all true statements.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Both particles trace the same parabola, 
          but they may move along it at different rates.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        Correct. Both parameterizations describe the curve <m>y=x^2</m>, 
        but the parameter changes how the curve is traced.
      </p>
    </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice correct="no">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The particles trace different curves because the equations are not identical.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback><p>Different parameterizations can describe the same geometric curve.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice correct="no">
      <statement><p>Since both parametrizations describe the same parabola, so
        <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m> is equal to <m>\dfrac{d\overline{y}}{d\overline{x}}</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Both particles move along the parabola <m>y=x^2</m>, but at different speed.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
    <!-- <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m> \dfrac{d\overline{y}}{d\overline{x}}</m> is twice <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m>.
      </p></statement>
      <feedback><p>There is no reason they must move in opposite directions.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = 2\dfrac{d\overline{y}}{d\overline{x}}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Correct. <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = 2t</m> and \dfrac{d\overline{y}}{d\overline{x}} = 4t.</p></feedback>
    </choice> -->
 <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m> is half of <m>\dfrac{d\overline{y}}{d\overline{x}}</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Correct. The second particle moves at twice the speed of the first particle.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>The second particle is faster than the first, so 
        <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} \lt \dfrac{d\overline{y}}{d\overline{x}}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Correct. The second particle moves at twice the speed of the first particle.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
 <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>Both particles have constant acceleration.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Correct. For the first particle the acceleration is 2 and for the second is 4 at any time <m>t</m></p></feedback>
    </choice>
    
  </choices>
</exercise>


  <exercise xml:id="sec10-3-concept-match-01" label="sec10-3-concept-match-01">
      <title>Exercise: Match each condition with its geometric interpretation.</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Match each condition for a parametric curve with the correct interpretation.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <cardsort>
      <match>
        <premise order="1"><m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}=0,\ \dfrac{dx}{dt}\neq 0</m></premise>
        <response>Horizontal tangent line</response>
      </match>
      <match>
        <premise order="2"><m>\dfrac{dx}{dt}=0,\ \dfrac{dy}{dt}\neq 0</m></premise>
        <response>Horizontal normal line</response>
      </match>
      <match>
        <premise order="3"><m>\dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2}&gt;0</m></premise>
        <response>Concave up</response>
      </match>
      <match>
        <premise order="4"><m>\dfrac{dx}{dt}>0</m>, <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}>0</m></premise>
        <response>The curve <m>y=y(x)</m> is increasing near <m>x</m>.</response>
      </match>
      <match>
        <response>Constant speed</response>
      </match>
      <match>
        <response>Clockwise motion</response>
      </match>
     <match>
        <response>The curve <m>y=y(x)</m> is decreasing near <m>x</m>.</response>
      </match> 
    </cardsort>
  </exercise>

