<exercise xml:id="ex-10-3-conceptual-concavity-arclength" label="mathematical-multiple-choice-multiple-answers">
  <title>Exercise: Select all that apply</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let a smooth curve be given by parametric equations <m>x=f(t)</m> and <m>y=g(t)</m> on
      <m>a\le t\le b</m>. Which of the following statements are true?
      Select all that apply.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <choices>
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The arc length of the curve from <m>t=a</m> to <m>t=b</m> is
          <m>\displaystyle L=\int_a^b \sqrt{\left(\frac{dx}{dt}\right)^2+\left(\frac{dy}{dt}\right)^2}\,dt</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. This is the standard arc length formula for a parametrically defined curve.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          To determine concavity of a parametric curve, one typically studies
          <m>\dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2}</m>, not just <m>\dfrac{d^2y}{dt^2}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Concavity with respect to the graph in the <m>xy</m>-plane is determined by
          <m>\dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2}</m>, since this describes how the slope <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m>
          changes as <m>x</m> changes.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>\dfrac{d^2y}{dt^2}>0</m> on an interval, then the parametric curve must be concave up there.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Incorrect. Concavity of a parametric curve depends on <m>\dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2}</m>, not merely
          on <m>\dfrac{d^2y}{dt^2}</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The arc length can always be found by integrating
          <m>\displaystyle \int_a^b \left(\frac{dy}{dx}\right)\,dt</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Incorrect. Arc length depends on the total rate of change in both coordinates, so both
          <m>\dfrac{dx}{dt}</m> and <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}</m> are needed.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m> is increasing as <m>x</m> increases, then the curve is concave down.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Incorrect. If <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m> is increasing as <m>x</m> increases, then the curve is
          concave up.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
  </choices>
  <hint>
    <p>
      Separate the ideas:
      <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m> gives slope,
      <m>\dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2}</m> gives concavity,
      and arc length measures the total distance traveled along the curve.
    </p>
  </hint>
</exercise>

