<!-- <exercise label="parsons-10-3-arc-length-specific-1" language="math">
  <title> Build the Arc Length Integral </title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      The curve is given parametrically by <m>x=t</m> and <m>y=t^2</m> for
      <m>0\le t\le 1</m>.
      Arrange the blocks to form the integral that gives the arc length of the curve.
      Not all blocks will be used.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <blocks layout="horizontal" randomize="yes">
    <block order="1"><m>L</m></block>
    <block order="2"><m>=</m></block>
    <block order="3"><m>\displaystyle\int_0^1</m></block>
    <block order="4"><m>\sqrt{1+4t^2}</m></block>
    <block order="5"><m>\,dt</m></block>
    <block correct="no"><m>\sqrt{t^2+4t^4}</m></block>
    <block correct="no"><m>\sqrt{1+2t}</m></block>

  </blocks>

  <hint>
    <p>
      First compute <m>\dfrac{dx}{dt}</m> and <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}</m>, then use
      <m>L=\int_a^b\sqrt{\left(\dfrac{dx}{dt}\right)^2+\left(\dfrac{dy}{dt}\right)^2}\,dt</m>.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      <m>L=\displaystyle\int_0^1\sqrt{1+4t^2}\,dt</m>
    </p>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Since <m>x=t</m>, we have <m>\dfrac{dx}{dt}=1</m>. Since <m>y=t^2</m>,
      we have <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}=2t</m>. Therefore,
      <m>
        L=\int_0^1 \sqrt{\left(\dfrac{dx}{dt}\right)^2+\left(\dfrac{dy}{dt}\right)^2}\,dt
        =\int_0^1 \sqrt{1^2+(2t)^2}\,dt
        =\int_0^1 \sqrt{1+4t^2}\,dt.
      </m>
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise> -->

<exercise label="horizontal-parson-arc-length-specific-hard" language="math">
  <title>Build the Arc Length Integral</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the parametric curve
      <m>x(t)=t^3-3t,\quad y(t)=t^2+1,\quad -1\le t\le 2.</m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Arrange the blocks to form the correct expression for the arc length of the curve on the given interval.
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Note:</em> Some blocks are distractors and should not be used.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <blocks layout="horizontal" randomize="yes">
    <!-- Correct blocks -->
    <block order="1"><m>\int_{-1}^{2}</m></block>
    <block order="2">sqrt</block>
    <block order="3"><m>\Bigl(</m></block>
    <block order="3"><m>\left(3t^2-3\right)^2</m></block>
    <block order="4"><m>+</m></block>
    <block order="5"><m>4t^2</m></block>
    <block order="6"><m>\Bigr)</m></block>
    <block order="7"><m>\,dt</m></block>

    <!-- Distractors -->
    <block correct="no"><m>\int_{0}^{2}</m></block>
    <!-- <block correct="no"><m>\int_{-1}^{2}\left[\cdots\right]\,dt</m></block> -->
    <block correct="no"><m>\left(3t^2-3\right)</m></block>
    <block correct="no"><m>2t</m></block>
    <!--
    <block><m>\left(6t\right)^2</m></block>
    <block><m>\sqrt{\left(3t^2-3\right)^2-\left(2t\right)^2}</m></block>
    <block><m>\sqrt{\left(3t^2-3\right)+\left(2t\right)}</m></block>
    <block><m>\,dx</m></block>
    <block><m>\,ds</m></block>
    <block><m>\left(3t^2+3\right)^2</m></block> -->
  </blocks>

  <answer>
    <p>
      The correct arc length expression is
      <me>
        \int_{-1}^{2}\sqrt{\left(3t^2-3\right)^2+\left(2t\right)^2}\,dt.
      </me>
    </p>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      For a parametric curve <m>x=x(t)</m>, <m>y=y(t)</m>, the arc length on <m>a\le t\le b</m> is
      <me>
        L=\int_a^b \sqrt{\left(\frac{dx}{dt}\right)^2+\left(\frac{dy}{dt}\right)^2}\,dt.
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      Here,
      <me>
        \frac{dx}{dt}=3t^2-3,\qquad \frac{dy}{dt}=2t.
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      Therefore,
      <me>
        L=\int_{-1}^{2}\sqrt{\left(3t^2-3\right)^2+\left(2t\right)^2}\,dt.
      </me>
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

</exercises>
</section>